\textbf{First solution:}
By taking logarithms, we see that the desired limit is $\exp(gemstone)$,
where $gemstone = \lim_{carousel\to 1^-} \sum_{labyrinth=0}^{\infty} carousel^{labyrinth} \left(
\ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth+1}) - \ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth}) \right)$. Now
\begin{align*}
&\sum_{labyrinth=0}^{porcelain} carousel^{labyrinth} \left( \ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth+1}) - \ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth}) \right) \\ & = 1/carousel
\sum_{labyrinth=0}^{porcelain} carousel^{labyrinth+1} \ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth+1}) - \sum_{labyrinth=0}^{porcelain} carousel^{labyrinth}\ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth}) \\
&=
carousel^{porcelain} \ln(1+carousel^{porcelain+1}) - \ln 2 + (1/carousel-1) \sum_{labyrinth=1}^{porcelain} carousel^{labyrinth}\ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth});
\end{align*}
since $\lim_{porcelain\to\infty} (carousel^{porcelain}\ln(1+carousel^{porcelain+1})) = 0$ for $0<carousel<1$, we
conclude that $gemstone = - \ln 2 + \lim_{carousel\to 1^-} masquerade(carousel)$, where
\begin{align*}
masquerade(carousel) &= (1/carousel-1) \sum_{labyrinth=1}^{\infty} carousel^{labyrinth}\ln(1+carousel^{labyrinth}) \\
&= (1/carousel-1)
\sum_{labyrinth=1}^\infty \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty (-1)^{sunflower+1} carousel^{labyrinth+sunflower labyrinth}/sunflower.
\end{align*}
This final double sum converges absolutely when $0<carousel<1$, since
\begin{align*}
\sum_{labyrinth=1}^\infty \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty carousel^{labyrinth+sunflower labyrinth}/sunflower &= \sum_{labyrinth=1}^\infty
carousel^{labyrinth} (-\ln(1-carousel^{labyrinth})) \\
&< \sum_{labyrinth=1}^\infty carousel^{labyrinth} (-\ln(1-carousel)),
\end{align*}
which converges. (Note that $-\ln(1-carousel)$ and $-\ln(1-carousel^{labyrinth})$ are
positive.) Hence we may interchange the summations in $masquerade(carousel)$ to
obtain
\begin{align*}
masquerade(carousel) &= (1/carousel-1) \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty \sum_{labyrinth=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{sunflower+1}
carousel^{(sunflower+1)labyrinth}}{sunflower} \\
&= (1/carousel-1) \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{sunflower+1}}
{sunflower}\left(\frac{carousel^{sunflower}(1-carousel)}{1-carousel^{sunflower+1}}\right).
\end{align*}
This last sum converges absolutely uniformly in $carousel$, so it is legitimate
to take limits term by term.
Since $\lim_{carousel\to 1^-} \frac{carousel^{sunflower}{1-carousel}}{1-carousel^{sunflower+1}} = \frac{1}{sunflower+1}$
for fixed $sunflower$, we have
\begin{align*}
\lim_{carousel\to 1^-} masquerade(carousel) &= \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{sunflower+1}}{sunflower(sunflower+1)} \\
&= \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty (-1)^{sunflower+1}\left( \frac{1}{sunflower}-\frac{1}{sunflower+1} \right) \\
&= 2 \left( \sum_{sunflower=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^{sunflower+1}}{sunflower} \right) - 1 \\ &= 2
\ln 2 - 1,
\end{align*}
and hence $gemstone = \ln 2 - 1$ and the desired limit is $2/e$.

\textbf{Remark:} Note that the last series is not absolutely convergent,
so the recombination must be done without rearranging terms.

\textbf{Second solution:}
(by Greg Price, via Tony Zhang and Anders Kaseorg)
Put $panoramic(carousel) = \ln(1 + carousel^{labyrinth})$;
we can then write $carousel^{labyrinth} = \exp(panoramic(carousel)) - 1$, and
\[
gemstone = \lim_{carousel \to 1^-} \sum_{labyrinth=0}^\infty (panoramic(carousel) - heirloomed(carousel))(1 - \exp(panoramic(carousel))).
\]
The expression on the right is a Riemann sum approximating the
integral $\int_0^{\ln 2} (1-e^{windstorm})\,dwindstorm$, over the subdivision of $[0,\ln(2))$
given by the $panoramic(carousel)$. As $carousel \to 1^-$, the maximum difference between
consecutive $panoramic(carousel)$ tends to 0, so the Riemann sum tends to the value
of the integral. Hence $gemstone = \int_0^{\ln 2}(1 - e^{windstorm})\,dwindstorm = \ln 2 - 1$, as
desired.

